1
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:20,000
MY GIRL
English subtitles by Pippi Longstocking
January 1, 2009

2
00:00:53,100 --> 00:00:54,700
I was born jaundiced.

3
00:00:54,900 --> 00:00:57,900
Once I sat on a toilet seat
at a truck stop and caught hemorrhoids.

4
00:00:58,700 --> 00:01:01,700
I've learned to live with a chicken bone
lodged in my throat for three years.

5
00:01:02,900 --> 00:01:05,900
So I knew dad would be devastated
when he learned my latest affliction.

6
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:10,200
Dad, I don't want
to upset you...

7
00:01:10,800 --> 00:01:13,400
but my left breast is developing
significantly faster than my right.

8
00:01:13,400 --> 00:01:16,400
It can only mean one thing,
cancer. I'm dying.

9
00:01:19,900 --> 00:01:22,900
Sweetie, hand me the mayonnaise
out of the fridge.

10
00:01:37,200 --> 00:01:39,200
Who's in?
Raise your hand.

11
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:43,100
Are you coming or not,
Thomas J.?

12
00:01:43,100 --> 00:01:44,400
- I don't think so.
- I knew he wouldn't come.

13
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:46,600
I have to go home.

14
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:48,800
To play with his dolls.

15
00:01:49,300 --> 00:01:51,900
Leave him alone.
Come on. Let's go.

16
00:02:00,100 --> 00:02:01,400
You didn't pay me.

17
00:02:01,500 --> 00:02:03,600
How do I know
you'll show us one?

18
00:02:03,800 --> 00:02:05,300
You're such a baby.

19
00:02:05,700 --> 00:02:08,700
All right. Here.

20
00:02:10,100 --> 00:02:12,900
Follow me
and don't say a word.

21
00:02:20,300 --> 00:02:21,700
You ready?

22
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:36,800
You sure you want to see it?
Or are you yellow?

23
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:38,300
I'm not chicken.

24
00:02:38,700 --> 00:02:41,300
Lean forward.

25
00:02:45,300 --> 00:02:46,400
It's empty!

26
00:02:46,600 --> 00:02:49,600
- You're so weird.
- I want my money back.

27
00:02:50,700 --> 00:02:52,000
- I was afraid of this.
- Of what?

28
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:53,400
Sometimes
when we get them...

29
00:02:53,700 --> 00:02:56,700
they're not
completely dead.

30
00:02:57,700 --> 00:03:00,700
Like when they cut
a chicken's head off -

31
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:02,900
- and they still run around.
- You're full of shit.

32
00:03:03,500 --> 00:03:06,300
I bet she's roaming
around this house somewhere.

33
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:13,100
There she is
in the rocking chair.

34
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:37,500
Hi, Gramoo.

35
00:03:41,100 --> 00:03:44,000
Vada, would you bring down
my cigarettes?

36
00:03:52,900 --> 00:03:54,500
See you later.

37
00:03:56,300 --> 00:03:58,800
- Did you know he was my wood shop teacher?

38
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:00,000
- You took wood shop?

39
00:04:00,500 --> 00:04:03,200
I made a tie rack.

40
00:04:05,900 --> 00:04:07,600
- The fluid's mixed?
- Yes.

41
00:04:09,100 --> 00:04:10,900
Put them on the stool.

42
00:04:13,900 --> 00:04:16,900
Guess what?
I beat Thomas J. in Monopoly.

43
00:04:17,400 --> 00:04:20,000
The rack holds six ties.

44
00:04:20,300 --> 00:04:22,200
I still have mine.

45
00:04:22,700 --> 00:04:23,700
- Arthur!
- Vada!

46
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:26,700
- I beat Thomas J. in Monopoly.
- Good for you.

47
00:04:27,300 --> 00:04:30,300
Once you put hotels on Boardwalk
and Park Place, you're a shoo-in.

48
00:04:30,800 --> 00:04:32,600
- I like to buy railroads.

49
00:04:32,700 --> 00:04:34,200
- Vada, we're trying to work here.

50
00:04:46,100 --> 00:04:49,100
Cruella De Vil
stole all the puppies.

51
00:04:50,700 --> 00:04:52,000
Hand me the cannula.

52
00:04:52,800 --> 00:04:57,500
<i>There he was
just-a walkin' down the street</i>

53
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:02,700
- Vada!
- Dad?

54
00:05:02,900 --> 00:05:04,900
I'm embalming my high school teacher.

55
00:05:05,300 --> 00:05:06,600
Don't sing.

56
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:11,000
All right, Arthur.
Slide him to me a little bit.

57
00:05:11,300 --> 00:05:13,400
Alright, that's good.

58
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:16,900
CANCER OF PROSTATE

59
00:05:17,900 --> 00:05:20,900
Let's put him in a nice model C-501
bronze stainless "Eternal Journey".

60
00:05:22,100 --> 00:05:24,500
He'll look like a champion.

61
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:27,900
SULTENFUSS PARLOR

62
00:05:57,100 --> 00:05:59,000
Is Mr. Harry Sultenfuss in?

63
00:05:59,100 --> 00:06:00,800
Sure. Come on in.

64
00:06:14,600 --> 00:06:17,600
Have you had the unfortunate experience
of recently losing a loved one?

65
00:06:19,500 --> 00:06:21,800
Could I see your dad for a second?

66
00:06:23,700 --> 00:06:26,200
Dad! Somebody's here!

67
00:06:29,400 --> 00:06:32,400
He's downstairs working on Mr. Layton.
Prostate cancer.

68
00:06:33,100 --> 00:06:35,900
Once it hits your prostate,
you're a goner.

69
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:44,200
- How may I help you?
- I'm Shelly DeVoto.

70
00:06:45,500 --> 00:06:48,200
We spoke the other day
regarding the makeup artist job.

71
00:06:48,400 --> 00:06:50,700
It's still available, I hope?

72
00:06:50,700 --> 00:06:52,300
I think it's still available.

73
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:55,600
I'm a licensed cosmetologist.

74
00:06:55,800 --> 00:06:58,800
I worked for two years
at the Dino Raphael Salon.

75
00:06:59,500 --> 00:07:02,200
My customers cried
when I said I was leaving.

76
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:05,700
- Miss DeVoto...
- I have a wonderful disposition.

77
00:07:05,700 --> 00:07:07,300
I put people at ease.

78
00:07:07,600 --> 00:07:09,600
These people
are already at ease.

79
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:14,000
This is not a beauty parlor.
It's a funeral parlor.

80
00:07:15,800 --> 00:07:18,200
- They're dead?
- They are.

81
00:07:18,700 --> 00:07:19,900
Stiffs?

82
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:21,700
Deceased.

83
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:24,600
The ad just said
"makeup artist."

84
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:26,500
Excuse me a second,
will you?

85
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:27,900
Sure.

86
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:31,400
Hi, George.
This is a 1258.

87
00:07:31,400 --> 00:07:34,400
I didn't want
the burnished handles.

88
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:37,800
- Is that your camper?
- Yes. It is.

89
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,400
That's really cool.

90
00:07:41,900 --> 00:07:43,100
Hello.

91
00:07:44,100 --> 00:07:45,200
She's shy.

92
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:50,700
Put it back
in the display room.

93
00:07:53,900 --> 00:07:56,500
Daddy, how come
that coffin's so small?

94
00:07:56,900 --> 00:07:59,500
They come in all sizes,
just like shoes.

95
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:01,200
- Is it for a child?

96
00:08:01,900 --> 00:08:02,900
- Of course not.

97
00:08:02,900 --> 00:08:05,900
- Then who's it for?
- Short people. Very short people.

98
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,800
Excuse me.
What about the job?

99
00:08:10,700 --> 00:08:11,900
Pardon?

100
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:13,600
I need the job.

101
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:16,200
You still want it?
Even though...

102
00:08:16,600 --> 00:08:18,600
Sure. It's no big deal.

103
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:21,600
You see, all my former clients
will eventually die -

104
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:24,500
- and all your clients
used to be alive.

105
00:08:24,600 --> 00:08:26,500
So they have something
in common.

106
00:08:26,800 --> 00:08:29,600
You'd do hair and makeup
and answer the phone.

107
00:08:30,800 --> 00:08:32,400
OK, mr Sultenfuss. 

108
00:08:32,800 --> 00:08:34,600
You've got a deal..

109
00:08:34,700 --> 00:08:36,400
You can start right away.

110
00:08:36,500 --> 00:08:38,100
Call me Harry.

111
00:08:39,500 --> 00:08:42,500
Is this what you'd normally
wear for work?

112
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:46,400
Don't get me wrong.
I like it very much.

113
00:08:46,700 --> 00:08:49,600
I promise I'll take good
care of these people.

114
00:08:49,700 --> 00:08:52,200
They deserve it.
They're dead.

115
00:08:53,500 --> 00:08:55,500
All they've got left
is their looks.

116
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,200
Hey, look at this.
No feet.

117
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:15,900
Wow.
A real Evel Knievel.

118
00:09:16,600 --> 00:09:20,700
ONLY PICK UP TRUCKS ALLOWED
NO BICYCLES

119
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:29,400
What are you doing in my garage?!
Get out of here!

120
00:09:58,300 --> 00:10:00,000
Hi, Veda.
What's wrong today?

121
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:02,100
I'm very sick.

122
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:05,800
OK, take a seat.
I'll check if the doctor can see you.

123
00:10:08,600 --> 00:10:09,600
Vada's here.

124
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:12,300
She says she's sick.

125
00:10:12,400 --> 00:10:13,800
She looks all right.

126
00:10:15,900 --> 00:10:17,300
OK, he'll see you.

127
00:10:17,600 --> 00:10:19,400
Why don't you go in?

128
00:10:25,100 --> 00:10:27,700
Well, what is it?
I can handle it.

129
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:30,000
You are perfectly healthy.

130
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:32,800
That can't be.
I have all the classic symptoms.

131
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:35,800
Did they bring
Mr. Layton to your house today?

132
00:10:35,800 --> 00:10:36,600
Yes.

133
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:39,500
You've got to stop this. There's
absolutely nothing wrong with you.

134
00:10:48,700 --> 00:10:51,100
I'll just have to get
a second opinion.

135
00:10:56,300 --> 00:10:58,700
What did he say
is wrong with you?

136
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:02,000
The whole medical profession
is a crock.

137
00:11:02,100 --> 00:11:03,800
Hey, wait up for me!

138
00:11:20,400 --> 00:11:21,400
Look!

139
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:22,600
At what?

140
00:11:22,600 --> 00:11:24,800
That's Mr. Bixler.
Let's go talk to him.

141
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:27,200
I don't want to talk
to no teacher, it's summer!

142
00:11:27,200 --> 00:11:28,300
Hi, mr. Bixler!

143
00:11:28,900 --> 00:11:31,600
Mademoiselle Sultenfuss
and the amazing Dr. J.

144
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:33,800
- How's the summer treating you?
- It's OK.

145
00:11:33,900 --> 00:11:36,900
Mr. Bixler, I finished all the books
for summer reading.

146
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:40,300
Really? Already?
The summer's just begun.

147
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:43,000
Yes. Now I'm reading
"War and Peace" for fun.

148
00:11:43,100 --> 00:11:45,200
No wonder you're
my prize pupil.

149
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:46,900
What about you, Thomas J.?

150
00:11:46,900 --> 00:11:48,400
I haven't started.

151
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:49,900
Better get on his case, Vada.

152
00:11:49,900 --> 00:11:52,400
How come you're painting
this house?

153
00:11:52,600 --> 00:11:55,500
Well, I just bought it.
Now I'm fixing it up.

154
00:11:56,200 --> 00:11:58,600
This is one big house
for one single person.

155
00:11:59,400 --> 00:12:00,600
Well -

156
00:12:00,700 --> 00:12:02,400
- you never can tell.

157
00:12:03,900 --> 00:12:05,400
I might get a pet.

158
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:09,000
How are you going to pay
for this house if you're not working?

159
00:12:09,900 --> 00:12:12,900
Well, I'm going to teach
creative writing this summer.

160
00:12:13,100 --> 00:12:14,700
I'm doing some work.

161
00:12:14,700 --> 00:12:17,300
- How much does it cost?
- 35 dollars.

162
00:12:17,200 --> 00:12:18,700
What do you get for that?

163
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:21,600
Me. Two hours a week
talking about poetry.

164
00:12:22,200 --> 00:12:23,900
Is this an interrogation, Vada?

165
00:12:23,900 --> 00:12:26,900
No. Well, I guess I'll go home
and finish off "War and Peace."

166
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:31,300
It's summer.
You're kids. Go play.

167
00:12:38,200 --> 00:12:40,800
Want to go to Gray's Orchard
and pick some peaches?

168
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:42,400
No. I'm going home.

169
00:12:42,500 --> 00:12:44,500
Why? It's not dinner time yet.

170
00:12:44,400 --> 00:12:47,400
You're just like a dog.
You just go home to eat.

171
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:50,300
Don't pee on the hydrant!

172
00:13:08,700 --> 00:13:10,500
<i>Bill</i>

173
00:13:11,100 --> 00:13:14,100
<i>I love you so
I always will</i>

174
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:22,000
<i>I look at you
and see the passion</i>

175
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:29,800
<i>Oh, but am I ever gonna see my
wedding day?</i>

176
00:13:31,700 --> 00:13:33,900
Trooper Gwynn called.
There was a big accident on PA34.

177
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:35,600
They're bringing
in two tomorrow.

178
00:13:35,600 --> 00:13:38,600
Excuse me, Harry. I finished
Mr. Layton's hair, I think...

179
00:13:39,300 --> 00:13:40,700
What's wrong with her?

180
00:13:40,800 --> 00:13:43,800
She's pretending.
Vada, get up and eat your broccoli.

181
00:13:45,400 --> 00:13:47,200
I think it's my prostate.

182
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:51,200
How many removals did you say...?

183
00:13:52,100 --> 00:13:54,100
We have to do a V section tomorrow,
will you give me a hand?

184
00:13:54,700 --> 00:13:56,300
I guess so.

185
00:13:56,600 --> 00:14:00,700
Now, this isn't gonna be a repeat of that
snooker accident a few years ago?

186
00:14:01,200 --> 00:14:03,600
Don't knock that up, it's how
we got that new Cadillac.

187
00:14:03,500 --> 00:14:07,500
I know that, except I had a body in my
bedroom, you had a body in your bedroom.

188
00:14:07,300 --> 00:14:09,800
We were littered with people's bodies.

189
00:14:18,500 --> 00:14:20,100
- Who's winning?
- I am.

190
00:14:21,500 --> 00:14:24,000
Look! Vada and her
little boyfriend.

191
00:14:24,500 --> 00:14:26,000
He's not my boyfriend.

192
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,400
I bet she kisses him
on the lips.

193
00:14:28,300 --> 00:14:30,300
You think I'd kiss that ugly thing?

194
00:14:30,400 --> 00:14:31,700
Yeah, anyway.

195
00:14:32,600 --> 00:14:34,100
Come on. Let's go.

196
00:14:34,100 --> 00:14:36,400
Judy's father
owns the Bijou theater.

197
00:14:36,300 --> 00:14:39,300
We see all the movies
we want for free.

198
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:40,800
Maybe you can come sometime?

199
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:43,800
Eew, don't invite her.
She'll bring her boyfriend.

200
00:14:44,300 --> 00:14:47,300
<i>Vada and Thomas
Sittin' in a tree</i>

201
00:14:48,500 --> 00:14:51,500
<i>K-I-S-S-I-N-G</i>

202
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:54,500
<i>First comes love</i>

203
00:14:54,600 --> 00:14:56,500
<i>Then comes marriage</i>

204
00:14:56,500 --> 00:14:59,500
<i>Then comes Thomas J.
in the baby carriage</i>

205
00:15:01,100 --> 00:15:04,000
You know Vada, you shouldn't
let those girls upset you.

206
00:15:03,900 --> 00:15:06,900
I'm not upset.
I would never play with those girls.

207
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:10,400
I surround myself with people
I find intellectually stimulating.

208
00:15:16,300 --> 00:15:18,100
Want a piece of chocolate?

209
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:21,300
- Thomas J.?
- I'm allergic to it.

210
00:15:21,300 --> 00:15:23,900
- To chocolate?
- He's allergic to everything.

211
00:15:23,900 --> 00:15:24,800
Chocolate?

212
00:15:24,800 --> 00:15:26,400
To everything.

213
00:15:29,300 --> 00:15:31,000
That's a pretty ring you're wearing.

214
00:15:31,100 --> 00:15:33,500
It's a mood ring.

215
00:15:33,500 --> 00:15:35,700
It doesn't work. 
It's always black.

216
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:38,900
It's only black when you're around
because you put me in a bad mood.

217
00:15:39,500 --> 00:15:41,200
Maybe black
means you're happy.

218
00:15:41,600 --> 00:15:43,000
I don't think so.

219
00:15:43,600 --> 00:15:45,800
Shelly,
how can I get $35?

220
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:48,900
She's crazy. She wants to go
to school over the summer.

221
00:15:48,900 --> 00:15:51,400
It's not a real school.
It's a writing class.

222
00:15:51,300 --> 00:15:52,800
I want to be a writer.

223
00:15:52,700 --> 00:15:55,600
She only wants to go cause her
sweetie pie's the teacher.

224
00:15:55,900 --> 00:15:57,800
Shut your
big, fat mouth!

225
00:15:58,300 --> 00:16:00,300
I think you'd make
a fine writer.

226
00:16:00,500 --> 00:16:02,000
Did you ask your dad?

227
00:16:02,200 --> 00:16:03,700
He won't give it to me.

228
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:06,100
You don't know that.

229
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:08,200
Ask him.

230
00:16:09,500 --> 00:16:11,700
<i>Edith, what channel
is Cronkite on?</i>

231
00:16:11,800 --> 00:16:13,400
<i>Channel two, Archie.</i>

232
00:16:13,500 --> 00:16:14,800
<i>The one we don't watch
because you always say -</i>

233
00:16:14,800 --> 00:16:17,800
<i>- Walter Cronkite
is a communist.</i>

234
00:16:26,200 --> 00:16:28,300
<i>I never said that, Edith.</i>

235
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:30,100
<i>The man ain't all red.</i>

236
00:16:32,100 --> 00:16:34,300
<i>What's wrong with this?
Nothing's coming on.</i>

237
00:16:36,500 --> 00:16:38,900
Daddy, can I have $35?

238
00:16:39,100 --> 00:16:41,200
That's a lot
for a little girl.

239
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:44,000
It's for school.
A summer writing class.

240
00:16:44,500 --> 00:16:46,100
Any more soda left?

241
00:16:49,400 --> 00:16:51,700
Shelly thinks I'd be
a good writer.

242
00:16:52,300 --> 00:16:54,800
Last month you wanted to play violin.

243
00:16:54,800 --> 00:16:57,300
Then you wanted to be
a ventriloquist.

244
00:16:58,200 --> 00:16:59,300
Dad?

245
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:01,000
I love this guy.

246
00:17:02,600 --> 00:17:04,700
What?

247
00:17:05,700 --> 00:17:07,100
The money?

248
00:17:07,800 --> 00:17:09,600
Maybe next summer.

249
00:17:11,600 --> 00:17:14,400
<i>He forgot about the time
I wanted to be a magician.</i>

250
00:17:14,400 --> 00:17:17,100
<i>I was really great
at making myself disappear.</i>

251
00:17:22,900 --> 00:17:24,000
Want to play?

252
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,000
No, I've got to go
to a cemetery.

253
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:27,800
Keep your head up.

254
00:17:28,600 --> 00:17:31,000
Don't look at the ball,
look at me.

255
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:34,700
See? You were lookin'
at the ball.

256
00:17:35,600 --> 00:17:38,600
All right?
Keep your head up.

257
00:18:34,200 --> 00:18:37,200
Please!
Open the door, please!

258
00:18:37,300 --> 00:18:40,200
Someone open the door!
Please!

259
00:18:50,900 --> 00:18:52,100
Vada.

260
00:18:52,400 --> 00:18:53,600
What happened?

261
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:57,400
My ball.
I lost my ball.

262
00:18:58,600 --> 00:19:00,300
Come on.

263
00:19:06,500 --> 00:19:07,700
Excuse me, Harry?

264
00:19:09,600 --> 00:19:12,500
Could you take a look
at Mrs. Porter?

265
00:19:20,200 --> 00:19:23,000
Didn't I give you a picture
of what she looked like?

266
00:19:29,900 --> 00:19:31,300
You don't like it?

267
00:19:31,400 --> 00:19:33,300
This was
the Reverend Porter's wife.

268
00:19:33,300 --> 00:19:36,000
You have her looking
like a two-dollar hooker.

269
00:19:36,100 --> 00:19:37,900
I think she looks nice.

270
00:19:38,300 --> 00:19:39,700
Her lips are very thin.

271
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:42,800
I used the gloss
to give them a sensual quality.

272
00:19:43,400 --> 00:19:46,400
And her eyes
just needed a little definition.

273
00:19:47,100 --> 00:19:50,100
And her hair...
Nobody wears this hairdo in 1972.

274
00:19:50,700 --> 00:19:51,700
She did.

275
00:19:51,800 --> 00:19:54,700
This photo was taken a month ago
at the church food drive.

276
00:19:54,700 --> 00:19:57,700
I wanted to get past
the schoolmarm image.

277
00:19:58,600 --> 00:20:01,600
That wasn't an image.
She was an old schoolmarm.

278
00:20:02,600 --> 00:20:03,700
Fix it.

279
00:20:06,300 --> 00:20:07,500
Harry?

280
00:20:12,300 --> 00:20:14,100
I was just wondering...

281
00:20:14,500 --> 00:20:16,500
...if there's anything wrong with Vada.

282
00:20:16,500 --> 00:20:17,900
What do you mean?

283
00:20:17,900 --> 00:20:20,500
- The other night...
- Oh, that. She likes to play.

284
00:20:20,500 --> 00:20:22,900
I don't think so.

285
00:20:23,100 --> 00:20:25,000
I think she's confused
about death.

286
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:28,000
She was raised in a funeral home.
She knows a little about it.

287
00:20:28,400 --> 00:20:30,000
But Harry, I really think...

288
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:33,000
She's a happy eleven-year-old girl.
Look...

289
00:20:33,800 --> 00:20:36,800
...don't give me any advice
about my daughter, okay?

290
00:20:54,100 --> 00:20:55,700
There's Shelly!

291
00:20:58,300 --> 00:20:59,400
Hi!

292
00:20:59,400 --> 00:21:01,800
Can we look around
in your camper?

293
00:21:02,100 --> 00:21:04,900
Sure. I'll give you
the royal tour.

294
00:21:16,200 --> 00:21:19,200
This is the coolest thing. You
can really eat and sleep here?

295
00:21:21,800 --> 00:21:23,700
I'm going to drive us
to Liverpool.

296
00:21:23,700 --> 00:21:24,700
Liverpool?

297
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:26,500
Big Ringo fan.

298
00:21:28,200 --> 00:21:30,000
- Would you like a soda?
- I would.

299
00:21:30,100 --> 00:21:31,700
- Thomas?
- Yes please.

300
00:21:37,200 --> 00:21:38,500
What are you reading?

301
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:45,000
You shouldn't be looking at that.
It's too old for you.

302
00:21:45,400 --> 00:21:47,300
Did you read all these books?

303
00:21:47,600 --> 00:21:49,100
What are they about?

304
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:52,000
Mostly love
and romance.

305
00:21:53,400 --> 00:21:54,700
Eew, gross!

306
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,900
They're just fun to read.

307
00:21:57,700 --> 00:21:59,200
Here. Cheers.

308
00:22:03,800 --> 00:22:05,400
Are you married?

309
00:22:05,500 --> 00:22:07,400
No, I'm divorced.

310
00:22:07,700 --> 00:22:10,000
Daddy says it's bad
when people get divorced.

311
00:22:10,100 --> 00:22:13,100
I know. Sometimes married people find out
they can't live with each other.

312
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:15,500
The Meyers are divorced.

313
00:22:17,700 --> 00:22:19,800
Shelly, can I have a cookie?

314
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:23,600
Hey, where are all the cookies?

315
00:22:24,900 --> 00:22:27,500
Well, I guess you found
my secret hiding place.

316
00:22:28,100 --> 00:22:29,900
What are you saving for?

317
00:22:30,700 --> 00:22:32,300
Nothing in particular.

318
00:22:32,500 --> 00:22:34,700
Just putting it away for a rainy day.

319
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:39,800
I'm supposed to be home at
noon for lunch. Thanks, Shelly!

320
00:22:42,400 --> 00:22:43,500
Bye.

321
00:22:45,300 --> 00:22:47,900
Well, miss Vada, what do you say we head back?

322
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:50,000
- Can I use your bathroom first?
- Sure.

323
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:53,000
You don't have to wait. Daddy will
be mad if you're late.

324
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:06,600
"The great way is not difficult
for those with no preferences.

325
00:23:08,600 --> 00:23:12,900
With the absence of both love and hate,
everything becomes clear -

326
00:23:13,300 --> 00:23:14,900
and undisguised."

327
00:23:16,300 --> 00:23:19,100
That was written by a Chinese
philosopher in the year 600.

328
00:23:19,300 --> 00:23:22,300
Why would I bring that up
in a creative writing class?

329
00:23:24,600 --> 00:23:27,600
Because the absence of judgement
helps us to appreciate reality.

330
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:31,000
In other words -

331
00:23:31,100 --> 00:23:33,900
- I want you to listen
to your classmates' writing -

332
00:23:33,900 --> 00:23:36,400
- with a clear and open heart.

333
00:23:39,300 --> 00:23:40,900
OK, so who's gonna go first?

334
00:23:41,300 --> 00:23:42,400
I got one.

335
00:23:47,700 --> 00:23:49,800
"I sang a song for you to hear -

336
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:52,700
I painted a picture for you to see -

337
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:55,100
I picked a rose for you to smell -

338
00:23:55,400 --> 00:23:57,700
I planted grass for you to touch -

339
00:23:58,200 --> 00:24:00,100
But you didn't hear my song.

340
00:24:00,400 --> 00:24:02,300
You did not see my picture.

341
00:24:02,800 --> 00:24:05,800
You did not smell my rose and 
you did not touch my grass!"

342
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:08,700
Maybe she was outta town?

343
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:10,500
That's not funny!

344
00:24:10,800 --> 00:24:12,800
His poem is about futility!

345
00:24:13,400 --> 00:24:16,300
We toil in unrewarded obscurity.

346
00:24:16,700 --> 00:24:18,000
Now, I hear judgement.

347
00:24:18,100 --> 00:24:21,100
Don't forget the part about the 
open heart! Vada?

348
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:24,400
Is there something I can do for you?

349
00:24:24,700 --> 00:24:26,100
I paid the money.

350
00:24:26,900 --> 00:24:28,300
For this class?

351
00:24:30,100 --> 00:24:31,700
I wanna be a writer.

352
00:24:33,300 --> 00:24:36,300
But Vada, this is an
adult writing class!

353
00:24:38,800 --> 00:24:41,800
Hey, I think it's beautiful! She
wants to be a writer!

354
00:24:42,500 --> 00:24:44,900
More power to you, little sister!

355
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:46,000
Vada?

356
00:24:46,100 --> 00:24:47,900
You sure you wanna do this?

357
00:24:49,800 --> 00:24:52,000
OK, welcome to the class!

358
00:24:52,600 --> 00:24:54,200
Go find a seat.

359
00:24:59,900 --> 00:25:01,600
OK, who's next?

360
00:25:02,300 --> 00:25:04,800
I experienced something with my
boyfriend the other day -

361
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:06,700
- and I wrote a few words down.

362
00:25:06,700 --> 00:25:08,800
The floor is yours, Ronda!

363
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:14,600
"He covers me like a blanket -

364
00:25:14,800 --> 00:25:17,700
from the cold dark night.

365
00:25:18,400 --> 00:25:21,400
As I look into his eyes I know it's right.

366
00:25:22,900 --> 00:25:25,500
To touch, to feel.

367
00:25:26,300 --> 00:25:27,600
I know he's real.

368
00:25:29,200 --> 00:25:31,400
Flesh all a-mesh.

369
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:34,800
I can't fight it.

370
00:25:35,600 --> 00:25:39,100
There's no point.

371
00:25:40,100 --> 00:25:42,800
I wake up and light a joint."

372
00:25:55,800 --> 00:25:57,400
I wrote a poem, too.

373
00:25:57,500 --> 00:25:58,700
Please.

374
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:03,300
"Ode to Ice Cream"
by Vada Sultenfuss.

375
00:26:03,800 --> 00:26:06,800
"I like ice cream a whole lot.
It tastes good when days are hot.

376
00:26:06,900 --> 00:26:09,900
On a cone or in a dish,
this would be my only wish.

377
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:13,400
Vanilla, chocolate, rocky road,
even with pie a la mode.''

378
00:26:14,600 --> 00:26:16,400
That's all I've got so far.

379
00:26:16,800 --> 00:26:18,400
I hear that, Vada.

380
00:26:18,700 --> 00:26:23,000
"Flesh all a-mesh" or "rocky road",
it's about desire.

381
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:28,500
Vada, that's very sweet and itrhymes,
and that's all good, but...

382
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:34,400
You're not expressing to
me what's in your soul.

383
00:26:35,300 --> 00:26:40,100
I want you to show me how you see the world,
your fears or desires.

384
00:26:41,100 --> 00:26:42,800
Your innermost secrets.

385
00:26:43,200 --> 00:26:44,800
<i>My fears and secrets?</i>

386
00:26:45,800 --> 00:26:47,800
<i>I'm afraid I killed my mother.</i>

387
00:27:20,700 --> 00:27:25,800
<i>Can not do without Harry's wild about me!</i>

388
00:27:26,900 --> 00:27:28,000
Excuse me, Harry?

389
00:27:28,100 --> 00:27:31,100
I just wanted to let you know that flower's
were delievered.

390
00:27:31,100 --> 00:27:33,000
And the room is all setup.

391
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:34,000
Thanks.

392
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:38,000
Listen, I want to apologize for the other day
downstairs about Vada.

393
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:39,300
I was a little harsh.

394
00:27:39,300 --> 00:27:42,300
I shouldn't stick my nose in
other people's business.

395
00:27:42,500 --> 00:27:44,600
It's just that I like
Vada very much.

396
00:27:45,500 --> 00:27:49,600
After my wife died grandma moved in here
to help us take care of Vada.

397
00:27:51,400 --> 00:27:53,000
They were very close.

398
00:27:53,700 --> 00:27:56,600
But lately as her mind's been wandering...

399
00:27:56,600 --> 00:27:58,900
Vada has been acting kinda crazy.

400
00:27:59,800 --> 00:28:01,600
I'm sure she'll snap out of it though.

401
00:28:02,900 --> 00:28:04,400
I'm sure she will.

402
00:28:07,500 --> 00:28:09,300
Nothing's biting today.

403
00:28:09,900 --> 00:28:11,700
Maybe they had a big breakfast.

404
00:28:12,700 --> 00:28:15,300
I'm gonna be an acrobat
when I grow up.

405
00:28:15,700 --> 00:28:18,400
Big deal, I can do that too!
Thomas J., you got something!

406
00:28:21,400 --> 00:28:22,500
Hurry!

407
00:28:23,200 --> 00:28:24,400
I'm trying.

408
00:28:25,100 --> 00:28:26,500
Reel it in!

409
00:28:36,900 --> 00:28:38,600
It's a sunny, throw it back.

410
00:28:39,600 --> 00:28:42,600
I don't like touching fish. I'll
pull the hook out without touching it.

411
00:28:43,500 --> 00:28:45,700
You're hurting him, don't kill him!

412
00:28:51,300 --> 00:28:52,600
Darn hook.

413
00:28:53,200 --> 00:28:54,900
I'm bleeding.
Did it get away?

414
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:56,500
Go look.

415
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:01,300
Yeah, it got away.
Come on, let's go.

416
00:29:01,500 --> 00:29:03,300
Hey, we can become blood brothers!

417
00:29:03,700 --> 00:29:05,000
No, I don't wanna.

418
00:29:05,100 --> 00:29:07,000
You could pick that
scab on your arm.

419
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:08,500
It's a mosquito bite.

420
00:29:09,100 --> 00:29:10,300
It'll bleed.

421
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:11,900
If I do it, can we go?

422
00:29:17,500 --> 00:29:19,200
OK, rub them together.

423
00:29:23,800 --> 00:29:26,000
Now we're blood brothers for life.

424
00:29:30,900 --> 00:29:32,800
DEATH NOTICE

425
00:29:40,100 --> 00:29:41,100
Hi.

426
00:29:42,400 --> 00:29:44,400
Hi, what can I do for you?

427
00:29:45,300 --> 00:29:48,300
Nothing, I was just wondering
what you were doing.

428
00:29:48,600 --> 00:29:50,200
Nothing, I'm just typing
up a funeral notice.

429
00:29:50,200 --> 00:29:52,900
When someone dies,
we put one in the paper.

430
00:29:52,900 --> 00:29:55,400
It's a service
we provide for the family.

431
00:30:00,600 --> 00:30:04,600
"Bader, Lorenzo. Died June 22, 1972.

432
00:30:05,300 --> 00:30:07,700
Devoted husband to Nicolette.

433
00:30:07,900 --> 00:30:10,900
Cherished father
of Fabrizio and Heidi.

434
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
In lieu of flowers, please send
donations to the Holy Name Society."

435
00:30:16,400 --> 00:30:17,900
I wrote that.

436
00:30:18,600 --> 00:30:20,200
No kidding?

437
00:30:20,400 --> 00:30:22,300
It's good! "In lieu of."

438
00:30:22,400 --> 00:30:23,900
I love that word, "lieu".

439
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:26,800
I prefer it to "instead", it
has  more dignity

440
00:30:27,500 --> 00:30:29,400
"In lieu", "instead".

441
00:30:29,900 --> 00:30:31,100
No contest.

442
00:30:31,800 --> 00:30:33,300
It's no big deal

443
00:30:33,300 --> 00:30:34,400
Harry...

444
00:30:34,600 --> 00:30:37,400
You have to learn
how to take a compliment.

445
00:30:37,400 --> 00:30:39,200
Movies! Movies...

446
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:45,500
"Love Story" at the drive-in! Cried
my eyes out! Did you see it?

447
00:30:46,500 --> 00:30:48,500
I haven't been to the movies in ages!

448
00:30:48,500 --> 00:30:50,300
I love to see movies.

449
00:30:50,500 --> 00:30:52,300
Especially at the drive-in.

450
00:30:52,700 --> 00:30:55,700
I don't think there's anything
more romantic than going to the drive-in.

451
00:30:59,400 --> 00:31:01,400
I'll let you back to work.

452
00:31:07,500 --> 00:31:09,200
I do enjoy playing bingo.

453
00:31:09,400 --> 00:31:12,400
If you'd like to join me
tomorrow night, you're welcome to.

454
00:31:26,500 --> 00:31:27,800
Hi Vada.

455
00:31:31,100 --> 00:31:32,600
- Are you going out somewhere?
- No.

456
00:31:34,300 --> 00:31:35,800
So how come you're
putting lipstick on?

457
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:38,100
A girl's always gotta look her best.

458
00:31:38,400 --> 00:31:40,100
I think lipstick looks fake.

459
00:31:40,700 --> 00:31:42,700
No one's lips are like that color.

460
00:31:42,900 --> 00:31:45,000
- Have you ever tried any?
- No.

461
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:47,600
Come here, sit down.

462
00:31:57,900 --> 00:32:00,200
Go like this.
A little less.

463
00:32:07,100 --> 00:32:08,600
Now first we blot.

464
00:32:15,600 --> 00:32:17,100
Take a look.

465
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:19,800
It looks real nice on you.

466
00:32:20,100 --> 00:32:22,200
Shelly, do you think I'm pretty?

467
00:32:22,600 --> 00:32:25,000
Yes Vada, I think you are very pretty.

468
00:32:25,400 --> 00:32:27,700
You got these great, big -

469
00:32:28,100 --> 00:32:29,800
sparkling eyes.

470
00:32:29,700 --> 00:32:31,800
The cutest little nose.

471
00:32:32,100 --> 00:32:33,600
And amazing mouth.

472
00:32:35,400 --> 00:32:37,500
The boys at school
don't think I am.

473
00:32:37,700 --> 00:32:39,000
They'll come around.

474
00:32:39,400 --> 00:32:44,000
Close your eyes. I want to bring out
the gorgeous color in them.

475
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:48,400
Now, the first rule in
applying eye make-up -

476
00:32:48,500 --> 00:32:51,500
- is you can never wear enough
blue eye shadow.

477
00:32:52,200 --> 00:32:54,400
Do you like putting make-up on people?

478
00:32:55,700 --> 00:32:58,700
I've been trying to get to Hollywood
to do make-up for the movie stars -

479
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:03,000
- but I haven't gotten there yet.

480
00:33:08,300 --> 00:33:09,700
Open your eyes.

481
00:33:14,600 --> 00:33:17,600
Shelly, I would definitely hold off
on that Hollywood thing.

482
00:33:31,500 --> 00:33:33,800
Your lip bleeding?

483
00:33:33,900 --> 00:33:35,500
What's wrong with your eyes?

484
00:33:35,500 --> 00:33:37,600
A girl can never wear enough eye shadow!

485
00:33:37,600 --> 00:33:39,300
Where's your bike?

486
00:33:39,800 --> 00:33:42,400
In the garage. Walk me over.

487
00:33:47,100 --> 00:33:49,400
It's only a garage, come on!

488
00:33:51,400 --> 00:33:53,500
One of my streamers is gone.

489
00:33:54,200 --> 00:33:56,000
It probably fell off in here.

490
00:33:58,500 --> 00:34:00,200
Hey, look at this!

491
00:34:00,300 --> 00:34:02,200
That was Gramoo's.

492
00:34:02,500 --> 00:34:04,000
It's a phrenology chart.

493
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:07,700
They used to study the bones in your head
to see if you had a good personality or not.

494
00:34:08,700 --> 00:34:11,000
Come here, I'll diagnose your head.

495
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:12,200
I don't wanna.

496
00:34:12,200 --> 00:34:13,900
Come on, it's fun.

497
00:34:22,900 --> 00:34:25,100
- Interesting.
- What?

498
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:26,800
You have no personality.

499
00:34:26,900 --> 00:34:29,400
-Where does it say that?
-Never mind.

500
00:34:31,800 --> 00:34:33,500
Is that your dad?

501
00:34:34,300 --> 00:34:35,300
Yes.

502
00:34:35,900 --> 00:34:37,600
Who's that with your dad?

503
00:34:43,600 --> 00:34:45,000
It's my mother.

504
00:34:45,600 --> 00:34:46,900
Do you remember her?

505
00:34:48,600 --> 00:34:50,500
Gramoo said she's in heaven.

506
00:34:50,800 --> 00:34:52,600
What do you think it's like?

507
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:54,300
- What?
- Heaven!

508
00:34:55,300 --> 00:34:56,400
I think...

509
00:34:57,300 --> 00:34:59,800
... everybody gets
their own white horse.

510
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:03,000
And all they do is ride them and
