You told everybody where you were going.
I'm here for the motor home.

768
00:52:58,200 --> 00:53:01,200
- No, I bought it. I paid for it.
- These two people do not have a good relationship.

769
00:53:01,300 --> 00:53:04,300
I've been living in it.
The camper is mine!

770
00:53:04,400 --> 00:53:08,100
Excuse me, "mutual asset."
That's what the lawyer said.

771
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:10,100
Not Shelly's recreational vehicle.

772
00:53:10,100 --> 00:53:12,600
Keep your voice down!
My boss is watching us.

773
00:53:12,700 --> 00:53:14,100
I'm impressed!

774
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:17,000
Oh God, I guess I have
to introduce you now.

775
00:53:21,200 --> 00:53:25,000
This is Harry, Phil,
Gramoo and Vada Sultenfuss.

776
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:28,600
Vada Sultenfuss?
Tough break!

777
00:53:28,500 --> 00:53:30,100
I like my name.

778
00:53:30,100 --> 00:53:32,000
This is Danny and Ralph.

779
00:53:32,000 --> 00:53:34,600
They own the Dino Raphael
Salon in Detroit.

780
00:53:35,100 --> 00:53:36,100
We just to be married.

781
00:53:36,400 --> 00:53:38,200
Are you here to take Shelly back?

782
00:53:38,300 --> 00:53:39,500
It's nice to meet you.

783
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:43,000
We've got burgers and hot dogs
here if you'd like to join us.

784
00:53:43,400 --> 00:53:45,200
Can't stay. I'm here because my wife...

785
00:53:45,200 --> 00:53:47,700
Ex!

786
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:51,000
My ex-wife seems to have
ripped off my camper.

787
00:53:52,700 --> 00:53:55,300
Honestly Harry, he got the Mustang.
I promise.

788
00:53:55,200 --> 00:53:58,200
I don't think so, I've got a copy
of the property settlement here.

789
00:53:58,400 --> 00:54:01,200
Shit! This is my lease.

790
00:54:01,400 --> 00:54:04,200
Damn it. I keep forgetting
things. Getting senile.

791
00:54:05,400 --> 00:54:06,600
What?

792
00:54:08,500 --> 00:54:10,300
I know you've suffered
a terrible loss...

793
00:54:10,300 --> 00:54:13,100
and there's nothing
anyone can do to comfort you.

794
00:54:13,100 --> 00:54:17,200
I urge you to focus on the times
you had with the camper...

795
00:54:17,300 --> 00:54:20,000
The trips you took,
the sights you saw...

796
00:54:20,100 --> 00:54:23,100
Those days are gone, but they'll
live on in your heart forever.

797
00:54:23,800 --> 00:54:25,100
Is he boinking you?

798
00:54:25,300 --> 00:54:28,300
That's a real bonehead thing to say!

799
00:54:28,900 --> 00:54:30,400
Look, you're not gonna
take Shelly's camper.

800
00:54:30,800 --> 00:54:33,300
- Oh, no?
- It's her home. It's where she lives.

801
00:54:33,300 --> 00:54:34,600
Oh really!

802
00:54:34,700 --> 00:54:37,200
Really? Fine. Go cook.
Give me the goddamn keys!

803
00:54:37,200 --> 00:54:38,800
- Come on!
- That hurts!

804
00:54:40,600 --> 00:54:42,100
What you do that for?

805
00:54:42,100 --> 00:54:44,300
- Who are you?
- I'm his brother.

806
00:54:44,600 --> 00:54:47,600
Then you'll be visiting us quite often.

807
00:54:47,600 --> 00:54:48,700
Why?

808
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:51,300
Because if he ever tries to take
Shelly's camper again -

809
00:54:51,300 --> 00:54:53,700
- I'm gonna bury him in my front yard.

810
00:54:58,100 --> 00:54:59,800
Your father's a savage!

811
00:55:09,800 --> 00:55:11,400
Well, you were pretty great!

812
00:55:11,900 --> 00:55:13,600
Is it really your camper?

813
00:55:23,900 --> 00:55:25,800
Can we see them from the back yard?

814
00:55:25,800 --> 00:55:27,700
You can get the general idea.

815
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:32,700
There they are.

816
00:55:32,900 --> 00:55:34,900
They always look the same every year.

817
00:55:36,400 --> 00:55:37,500
Look!

818
00:55:41,100 --> 00:55:42,500
Did you -

819
00:55:43,100 --> 00:55:44,300
- love him?

820
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:50,600
I would never marry anybody
I didn't love.

821
00:55:53,400 --> 00:55:55,200
He must like Shelly.

822
00:55:55,600 --> 00:55:58,400
I never saw him hit
anyone in his life.

823
00:55:59,100 --> 00:56:00,300
He likes her.

824
00:56:02,100 --> 00:56:03,800
Does he love her?

825
00:56:04,800 --> 00:56:05,900
Probably.

826
00:56:08,400 --> 00:56:09,800
Do you like her?

827
00:56:10,700 --> 00:56:11,700
Yes I do -

828
00:56:12,600 --> 00:56:15,200
- and I think she's very
good for your father.

829
00:56:15,100 --> 00:56:16,200
Why?

830
00:56:17,600 --> 00:56:20,500
After your mother died,
he was sad all the time.

831
00:56:20,600 --> 00:56:23,600
But before that,
he was pretty funny.

832
00:56:24,800 --> 00:56:25,900
Really?

833
00:56:30,300 --> 00:56:32,500
Now when I see him with Shelly -

834
00:56:33,200 --> 00:56:35,800
- sometimes he seems
like the old Harry.

835
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:37,700
My dad was funny?

836
00:56:39,400 --> 00:56:42,400
He wasn't one of the Marx
Brothers but made me laugh.

837
00:56:46,600 --> 00:56:48,700
<i>My uncle fought in the Korean War.</i>

838
00:56:48,700 --> 00:56:53,400
<i>He had a steel plate put in his head.
Daddy said he didn't come back the same.</i>

839
00:56:53,300 --> 00:56:57,300
<i>One night, we picked up a radio
station from Oklahoma in his teeth.</i>

840
00:56:57,900 --> 00:56:59,700
<i>It was really neat.</i>

841
00:57:03,800 --> 00:57:06,500
- Can't you see it?
- What?

842
00:57:06,500 --> 00:57:08,000
Can't you see it?

843
00:57:09,100 --> 00:57:10,100
It's there.

844
00:57:10,300 --> 00:57:13,000
Vada there is no chicken
bone stuck in your throat.

845
00:57:13,900 --> 00:57:16,800
Dr. Welty, are you
sure those are yours?

846
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:24,000
So you fill it with water, like
this. And you've got a water gun!

847
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:26,000
Cool! Can I get one for Vada?

848
00:57:26,100 --> 00:57:27,700
Oh yes, yes.

849
00:57:28,400 --> 00:57:30,700
Thomas, let me ask you a question.

850
00:57:31,200 --> 00:57:33,500
Does Vada ever tell you why
she comes here so much?

851
00:57:33,500 --> 00:57:34,800
She's dying.

852
00:57:34,800 --> 00:57:36,000
Do you think she is?

853
00:57:36,101 --> 00:57:36,601
No.

854
00:57:37,100 --> 00:57:38,800
And why do you think she says that?

855
00:57:38,900 --> 00:57:41,400
Because she gets scared of all
those dead people in her house.

856
00:57:41,500 --> 00:57:44,500
You know that saying, " If you can't
beat them, join them''?

857
00:57:44,800 --> 00:57:47,300
If she's one of them,
she won't be as scared.

858
00:57:47,300 --> 00:57:48,700
You know what I think?

859
00:57:48,900 --> 00:57:51,700
I think Vada's very lucky
to have a friend like you.

860
00:57:52,200 --> 00:57:54,000
She's my best friend.

861
00:57:55,100 --> 00:57:57,100
Miss Vada, how are you feeling?

862
00:57:57,900 --> 00:58:00,300
As good as can be expected.

863
00:58:02,400 --> 00:58:04,200
- Hey Vada, guess what we've got?
- What?

864
00:58:04,400 --> 00:58:05,400
This!

865
00:58:05,300 --> 00:58:07,800
Hey, you! I'm gonna get you!

866
00:58:08,600 --> 00:58:10,100
I'll get you!

867
00:58:10,100 --> 00:58:11,500
Give me that, you creep!

868
00:58:14,300 --> 00:58:15,800
I just got you!

869
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:17,400
No, you didn't!

870
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:20,100
What?

871
00:58:20,200 --> 00:58:22,300
- There's a bee hive.
- So?

872
00:58:22,700 --> 00:58:24,100
Stand back.

873
00:58:26,100 --> 00:58:27,200
Are you crazy?

874
00:58:27,300 --> 00:58:28,800
You'll get stung!

875
00:58:28,700 --> 00:58:30,500
You're right. Let's knock it down.

876
00:58:30,500 --> 00:58:32,200
What do you want if for, anyway?

877
00:58:32,300 --> 00:58:34,000
Cause they're neat.

878
00:58:41,300 --> 00:58:42,500
Got it!

879
00:58:43,800 --> 00:58:46,700
My mood ring fell off!
I gotta find it!

880
00:58:53,600 --> 00:58:56,100
They're alive!
Run for your life!

881
00:59:08,200 --> 00:59:09,900
Run faster! They're after us!

882
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:11,500
I am running faster.

883
00:59:12,500 --> 00:59:14,100
- Hurry!
- Jump in the water!

884
00:59:14,300 --> 00:59:15,700
I have my clothes on!

885
00:59:15,700 --> 00:59:16,900
Do it!

886
00:59:31,200 --> 00:59:32,600
Vada, is that you?

887
00:59:32,800 --> 00:59:33,700
Yes.

888
00:59:33,700 --> 00:59:36,300
Guess what? We're going
to the carnival tonight.

889
00:59:36,400 --> 00:59:38,200
Be ready to go in 10 minutes.

890
00:59:38,800 --> 00:59:40,900
Shelly's coming with us.

891
00:59:50,800 --> 00:59:52,800
Vada, what's your favorite ride?

892
00:59:52,800 --> 00:59:54,500
I like the freak show.

893
00:59:55,000 --> 00:59:56,300
I know, I know.

894
00:59:56,500 --> 00:59:59,500
I know. Let's go on the
"sit on the bench and rest ride."

895
00:59:59,600 --> 01:00:02,600
I don't think that roller coaster
agreed with your dad's stomach.

896
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:05,100
You know Vada, you have to
watch what you eat here.

897
01:00:05,100 --> 01:00:08,100
Once I went to a carnival
with my cousins, David and Frank.

898
01:00:08,200 --> 01:00:09,600
They ate hot dogs -

899
01:00:09,500 --> 01:00:11,800
- and the next day
came down with nephritis.

900
01:00:11,800 --> 01:00:13,600
Nephritis is a kidney disease.

901
01:00:13,900 --> 01:00:16,300
- You don't get it from hot dogs.
- I'm not a doctor!

902
01:00:16,300 --> 01:00:19,100
All I know is, the next day
they had high fevers -

903
01:00:19,100 --> 01:00:21,400
- and their faces got very fat.

904
01:00:21,400 --> 01:00:24,800
It baffled medical science.
They were in a magazine.

905
01:00:25,700 --> 01:00:28,100
They were! "Popular Mechanics"!

906
01:00:28,100 --> 01:00:29,900
No, "Popular Science".

907
01:00:30,200 --> 01:00:32,100
I don't know, it was "Popular".

908
01:00:32,200 --> 01:00:34,100
They're trying to hit that poor thing!

909
01:00:34,100 --> 01:00:35,900
Watch you don't knock out a fish.

910
01:00:36,900 --> 01:00:38,400
Just arc it.

911
01:00:41,600 --> 01:00:43,400
I don't know which ball's mine.

912
01:00:43,900 --> 01:00:45,400
I won! I won!

913
01:00:45,500 --> 01:00:46,800
Great!

914
01:00:46,700 --> 01:00:49,400
We have a winner!
There you go, little girl.

915
01:00:49,300 --> 01:00:50,900
See how easy it is, folks?

916
01:00:51,400 --> 01:00:53,800
Oh Vada, that's a gorgeous goldfish.

917
01:00:54,800 --> 01:00:56,400
Where'd you get that ring?

918
01:00:59,100 --> 01:01:00,500
Did you win it?

919
01:01:06,900 --> 01:01:08,500
Vada, we have something to tell you.

920
01:01:15,100 --> 01:01:16,900
Vada, we have some good news.

921
01:01:17,500 --> 01:01:19,700
Shelly and I are getting married.

922
01:01:21,600 --> 01:01:23,000
Oh, my fish!

923
01:01:26,500 --> 01:01:29,500
We're having the wedding sometime
near the end of the summer.

924
01:01:29,800 --> 01:01:31,700
You'll be OK, little fish.

925
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:37,600
Vada, would you like us
to get another goldfish?

926
01:01:37,600 --> 01:01:40,200
No, he's fine.

927
01:01:41,400 --> 01:01:44,000
Fish are very resilient animals.

928
01:01:44,900 --> 01:01:47,400
Don't worry, I won't
get another fish.

929
01:01:50,800 --> 01:01:52,100
The bumper car! The bumper car!

930
01:01:53,700 --> 01:01:56,700
For just 50 cents... a half dollar...
five dimes... ten nickels...

931
01:01:57,400 --> 01:02:01,600
We have a ride guaranteed to rearrange
all of your internal organs.

932
01:02:01,400 --> 01:02:02,700
Don't pass me by!

933
01:02:02,900 --> 01:02:05,000
That's the bumper car ride!

934
01:02:05,400 --> 01:02:09,800
Bumper cars! You can't go to a carnival
and not ride the bumper cars!

935
01:02:09,700 --> 01:02:11,400
I fall asleep at the wheel!

936
01:02:11,400 --> 01:02:13,400
I'll ride the bumper cars with you.

937
01:02:13,500 --> 01:02:15,600
Great, Vada! Come on.

938
01:02:20,100 --> 01:02:21,800
Two. I got the blue one!

939
01:02:26,700 --> 01:02:28,400
I'm gonna come get you.

940
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:38,100
Vada, keep your
hands on the wheel!

941
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:16,700
Careful, Vada, careful!

942
01:03:17,700 --> 01:03:18,900
Shelly, look out!

943
01:03:49,400 --> 01:03:51,700
- Hi, Vada!
- Hi, is Thomas J. home?

944
01:03:51,700 --> 01:03:53,400
Sure, come on in.

945
01:03:56,100 --> 01:03:57,300
Hi, Vada.

946
01:03:57,300 --> 01:03:59,600
- Hi, wanna ride bikes?
- Sure.

947
01:04:00,800 --> 01:04:02,700
- Did you make your bed?
- Yes.

948
01:04:03,100 --> 01:04:04,800
- Are you sure?
- It's made.

949
01:04:04,700 --> 01:04:05,800
Come here.

950
01:04:06,300 --> 01:04:08,200
You've got a milk moustache.

951
01:04:10,800 --> 01:04:12,100
Come on, let's go.

952
01:04:12,500 --> 01:04:13,900
Bye, Mrs. Sennett.

953
01:04:14,600 --> 01:04:16,600
- Bye, mum.
- Have fun, kids.

954
01:04:19,300 --> 01:04:20,800
I'm running away!

955
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:22,900
Where are you running to?

956
01:04:23,800 --> 01:04:27,200
To California. I'm going to Hollywood
to live with the Brady bunch.

957
01:04:27,400 --> 01:04:29,000
I wanna live with them too!

958
01:04:29,000 --> 01:04:31,800
You can't, they have enough kids.

959
01:04:31,800 --> 01:04:34,100
You'll have to live with
the Partridge Family.

960
01:04:34,900 --> 01:04:36,100
Really?

961
01:04:50,800 --> 01:04:52,100
That's it.

962
01:05:02,100 --> 01:05:04,600
- Get up!
- I'm tired of running away.

963
01:05:05,100 --> 01:05:07,800
Besides, we passed this place
two times already. 

964
01:05:07,800 --> 01:05:10,000
We're not getting nowhere.

965
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:13,600
So why are you running away?

966
01:05:14,600 --> 01:05:17,000
My dad gave Shelly a ring.

967
01:05:17,300 --> 01:05:18,600
Wow, was it a decoder ring?

968
01:05:19,300 --> 01:05:20,900
You're such a retard!

969
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:22,600
It was an engagement ring.

970
01:05:22,900 --> 01:05:24,400
They're getting married?

971
01:05:24,900 --> 01:05:26,300
So now you have a mother.

972
01:05:26,500 --> 01:05:27,800
I don't like her.

973
01:05:28,100 --> 01:05:29,900
I do. She's real funny.

974
01:05:30,900 --> 01:05:33,100
She likes you better than me.

975
01:05:38,900 --> 01:05:41,300
I'm hungry. I can't last any longer.

976
01:05:41,300 --> 01:05:42,600
Then go home, baby!

977
01:05:42,700 --> 01:05:44,800
I have to anyway, my
mum will be worried.

978
01:05:45,300 --> 01:05:47,400
Leave then! Some friend you are!

979
01:05:47,600 --> 01:05:49,900
You can come to my house for dinner.

980
01:05:50,600 --> 01:05:52,000
No, I'm hiding out.

981
01:05:52,600 --> 01:05:54,200
OK, see you.

982
01:06:54,300 --> 01:06:56,600
<i>Perhaps you didn't hear
what I said, Mr. Deeds.</i>

983
01:06:57,300 --> 01:07:00,300
<i>The whole Circle
fortune goes to you.</i>

984
01:07:00,800 --> 01:07:02,300
<i>I heard you, all right.</i>

985
01:07:02,300 --> 01:07:04,300
<i>20 million, that's
quite a lot, isn't it?</i>

986
01:07:04,600 --> 01:07:06,000
<i>It'll do in a pinch.</i>

987
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:09,000
<i>I wonder why he left me
all that money. I don't need it.</i>

988
01:07:11,400 --> 01:07:14,400
<i>In social studies we learned some
people stole the Lindbergh baby</i> -

989
01:07:14,500 --> 01:07:15,900
- <i>right out of his house.</i>

990
01:07:16,200 --> 01:07:18,900
<i>I think I'll sleep
with my window open tonight.</i>

991
01:07:23,100 --> 01:07:24,500
Oh, my God!

992
01:07:25,200 --> 01:07:26,300
Daddy!

993
01:07:34,900 --> 01:07:37,000
Vada, what's the matter?

994
01:07:37,900 --> 01:07:39,000
Where's daddy?

995
01:07:39,000 --> 01:07:41,300
- He just left, what's wrong?
- I'm hemorrhaging.

996
01:07:41,300 --> 01:07:42,500
What do you mean, you're hemorrhaging?

997
01:07:42,600 --> 01:07:45,300
I don't want or need your help!

998
01:07:45,800 --> 01:07:47,900
Vada, did this happen in the bathroom?

999
01:07:48,700 --> 01:07:51,000
- How old are you?
- I'm eleven and a half.

1000
01:07:51,800 --> 01:07:54,800
It's okay. Come upstairs.
We have to have a little talk.

1001
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:00,300
My mummy and daddy did that?

1002
01:08:00,800 --> 01:08:03,100
Actually, it's a very beautiful thing.

1003
01:08:04,300 --> 01:08:06,100
And look, there wouldn't have been a Vada!

1004
01:08:06,500 --> 01:08:08,200
I think it should be outlawed.

1005
01:08:08,600 --> 01:08:11,200
Believe me, some day you'll feel differently.

1006
01:08:11,900 --> 01:08:14,700
That's probably Thomas J.
I don't wanna see him.

1007
01:08:16,400 --> 01:08:17,900
It's not fair.

1008
01:08:18,300 --> 01:08:20,100
Nothing happens to boys!

1009
01:08:23,800 --> 01:08:24,800
Hi, Vada.

1010
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:26,200
Can you come out?

1011
01:08:26,900 --> 01:08:28,200
I don't know...

1012
01:08:28,500 --> 01:08:31,300
Please, it's real hot.
Maybe we can go swimming?

1013
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:35,600
No! Get out of here!

1014
01:08:37,000 --> 01:08:39,900
And don't come back for 5 to 7 days!

1015
01:08:56,700 --> 01:08:59,600
Gramoo, I'm going to the bathroom.
I'll be right back.

1016
01:09:02,200 --> 01:09:03,400
Stay here.

1017
01:09:29,100 --> 01:09:30,500
- Ready?
- Yeah.

1018
01:09:58,900 --> 01:10:01,900
<i>It's quarter to three</i>

1019
01:10:01,900 --> 01:10:04,900
<i>There's no one in the place,
but just you and me.</i>


1020
01:10:07,100 --> 01:10:10,000
<i>So set them up, Joe</i>

1021
01:10:09,900 --> 01:10:12,900
<i>I've got a little story
you ought to know</i>

1022
01:10:14,600 --> 01:10:17,600
<i>We're coming, my friend</i>

1023
01:10:18,400 --> 01:10:21,000
<i>To the end of a brief episode.</i>

1024
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:22,400
I'm so sorry.

1025
01:10:22,600 --> 01:10:25,000
It's OK, ma.

1026
01:10:25,000 --> 01:10:27,100
<i>So make it one for my baby.</i>

1027
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:29,600
<i>And one more for the road.</i>

1028
01:10:29,600 --> 01:10:31,000
Very very sorry.

1029
01:10:35,200 --> 01:10:37,600
What were you thinking?

1030
01:10:37,600 --> 01:10:39,700
It's your responsibility
to watch her!

1031
01:10:39,900 --> 01:10:42,900
Do you have any idea how
upset those people are in there?

1032
01:10:56,600 --> 01:10:59,200
Why do you think people
want to get married?

1033
01:10:59,600 --> 01:11:02,300
When you get older,
you just have to.

1034
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:05,000
I'm going to marry Mr. Bixler.

1035
01:11:05,200 --> 01:11:07,900
You can't marry a teacher.
It's against the law.

1036
01:11:07,900 --> 01:11:09,800
- Is not!
- Yes, it is.

1037
01:11:09,800 --> 01:11:12,800
'Cause then he'll give you all A's,
and it won't be fair.

1038
01:11:13,300 --> 01:11:14,500
Not true.

1039
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:19,500
Have you ever kissed anyone?

1040
01:11:21,000 --> 01:11:22,900
Like they do on TV?

1041
01:11:27,600 --> 01:11:30,600
Maybe we should, just to see
what's the big deal.

1042
01:11:31,800 --> 01:11:33,500
But, I don't know how!

1043
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:36,400
Here, practice on your arm like this.

1044
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:38,500
Like this?

1045
01:11:41,500 --> 01:11:43,400
OK, enough practice.

1046
01:11:43,800 --> 01:11:45,000
Close your eyes.

1047
01:11:45,400 --> 01:11:47,400
But then I won't be
able to see anything!

1048
01:11:47,300 --> 01:11:48,400
Just do it!

1049
01:11:53,600 --> 01:11:55,600
On the count of three.

1050
01:11:56,500 --> 01:11:57,600
One...

1051
01:11:58,500 --> 01:12:00,500
two... two and a half...

1052
01:12:01,400 --> 01:12:02,400
three!

1053
01:12:10,800 --> 01:12:13,400
Say something, it's too quiet!

1054
01:12:16,300 --> 01:12:18,000
Just hurry!

1055
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:21,200
"I pledge allegiance
to the flag -"

1056
01:12:21,400 --> 01:12:23,400
- "of the United
States of America -"

1057
01:12:23,700 --> 01:12:25,900
- "and to the republic 
for which it stands -"

1058
01:12:25,900 --> 01:12:31,500
- "one nation under God, indivisible
with liberty and justice for all."

1059
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:53,600
You better not tell anyone!

1060
01:12:53,600 --> 01:12:55,300
You better not either.

1061
01:12:56,300 --> 01:12:58,900
Let's spit on it.

1062
01:13:00,100 --> 01:13:02,300
See you tomorrow.

1063
01:13:03,200 --> 01:13:04,300
Vada?

1064
01:13:05,000 --> 01:13:06,100
What?

1065
01:13:07,100 --> 01:13:08,400
Would you think of me?

1066
01:13:09,000 --> 01:13:10,400
What?

1067
01:13:11,200 --> 01:13:13,500
If you don't marry Mr. Bixler.

1068
01:13:15,600 --> 01:13:16,900
I guess.

1069
01:14:02,900 --> 01:14:04,000
Yes!

1070
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:15,000
God, no!

1071
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:20,100
Get away!

1072
01:15:07,400 --> 01:15:08,700
What are you doing?

1073
01:15:09,100 --> 01:15:10,300
Feeding my fish.

1074
01:15:14,800 --> 01:15:17,700
- Is that the fish you won at the carnival?
- Yes.

1075
01:15:20,500 --> 01:15:22,200
He's getting big.

1076
01:15:26,500 --> 01:15:29,100
Vada, come here and
sit down for a minute.

1077
01:15:34,600 --> 01:15:36,900
Vada, something happened to
Thomas J. last night.

1078
01:15:39,000 --> 01:15:41,000
He stepped on a beehive.

1079
01:15:41,600 --> 01:15:43,500
I told him not to
tease those bees.

1080
01:15:44,100 --> 01:15:45,200
Did he get stung?

1081
01:15:48,900 --> 01:15:51,200
Maybe I should go over
and yell at him?

1082
01:15:53,500 --> 01:15:55,800
No, sweetheart,
you can't

1083
01:15:58,800 --> 01:15:59,900
Why not?

1084
01:16:03,500 --> 01:16:05,700
He was allergic to bees.

1085
01:16:07,100 --> 01:16:09,000
He's OK, isn't he?

1086
01:16:11,500 --> 01:16:13,400
There were just too many of them.

1087
01:16:30,400 --> 01:16:31,500
Dr. Welty!

1088
01:16:34,600 --> 01:16:36,300
Vada, what's wrong, sweety?

1089
01:16:36,500 --> 01:16:38,300
I can't breathe,
I'm suffocating!

1090
01:16:38,400 --> 01:16:41,100
Relax, let me look.

1091
01:16:41,100 --> 01:16:43,600
Come up here,
let me have a look.

1092
01:16:44,300 --> 01:16:48,300
It hurts, it hurts so bad!

1093
01:16:48,600 --> 01:16:50,300
What hurts Vada?

1094
01:16:50,600 --> 01:16:53,600
The bee stings!
I can't breathe!

1095
01:17:21,300 --> 01:17:24,300
I'll leave some food for you
at the door in case you get hungry.

1096
01:17:31,100 --> 01:17:33,200
Hi. Is Vada home?

1097
01:17:33,500 --> 01:17:37,500
Yes, but she's very upset
and she's not seeing anyone.

1098
01:17:38,800 --> 01:17:40,800
I'm Judy, I go to
school with her

1099
01:17:40,900 --> 01:17:43,700
I wanted to tell her
I'm sorry about Thomas J.

1100
01:17:44,700 --> 01:17:46,600
Maybe she'll feel better in
a couple of days.

1101
01:17:46,600 --> 01:17:48,000
Will you tell her
I came by?

1102
01:17:48,700 --> 01:17:50,800
Sure.

1103
01:18:00,100 --> 01:18:01,800
- Hi, Harry.
- Hi, reverend Moss.

1104
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:05,000
The Sennetts want to thank you for
taking care of things so quickly.

1105
01:18:17,500 --> 01:18:19,100
Vada, I see you took
your tray in.

1106
01:18:20,100 --> 01:18:22,700
Maybe you should come
down to the funeral?

1107
01:18:23,200 --> 01:18:24,800
Sometimes it helps.

1108
01:18:35,100 --> 01:18:36,600
She won't come out.

1109
01:18:38,600 --> 01:18:40,100
It's been a whole day.

1110
01:18:41,600 --> 01:18:43,700
You'll have to
do something, Harry.

1111
01:18:44,400 --> 01:18:45,800
The funeral's starting.

1112
01:18:45,800 --> 01:18:48,700
Open your eyes,
she's 11 years old!

1113
01:18:49,300 --> 01:18:51,200
Her only friend in the
world is dead!

1114
01:18:51,200 --> 01:18:53,600
I know that but what do
you want from me?

1115
01:18:53,700 --> 01:18:55,400
Stop hiding, Harry!

1116
01:18:56,300 --> 01:18:59,300
You run Harry.
When I first came here -

1117
01:19:00,100 --> 01:19:03,100
- the idea of working with dead
people didn't exactly thrill me.

1118
01:19:05,000 --> 01:19:07,400
When I saw a family lived here -

1119
01:19:08,100 --> 01:19:09,500
- I thought -

1120
01:19:10,700 --> 01:19:13,000
- "If I'm living
without a family" -

1121
01:19:13,500 --> 01:19:15,500
- "at least I can work
with one." -

1122
01:19:16,400 --> 01:19:19,100
"And maybe once in while get
invited in for supper."

1123
01:19:19,100 --> 01:19:21,200
Yeah, but when those suppers
are disrupted -

1124
01:19:21,200 --> 01:19:25,100
- because there's a car crash or there's a
fire or a little boy steps on a beehive?

1125
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:28,800
- I'm not asking you to stop
feeling for those people.

1126
01:19:31,000 --> 01:19:33,000
But life isn't just death, Harry.

1127
01:19:35,100 --> 01:19:37,100
Don't ignore the living -

1128
01:19:38,500 --> 01:19:40,300
- especially your daughter.

1129
01:19:43,700 --> 01:19:46,200
Excuse me Harry, Shelly, the
minister's about to begin.

1130
01:19:46,800 --> 01:19:48,600
Thank you, Arthur.

1131
01:20:02,200 --> 01:20:05,200
We are here to honour
Thomas J. Sennett.

1132
01:20:07,200 --> 01:20:12,200
He was born May 7, 1961,
in Madison, Pennsylvania.

1133
01:20:12,400 --> 01:20:16,200
He's survived by his loving parents
Charles and Susan Sennett, -

1134
01:20:16,600 --> 01:20:19,500
- his grandparents,
William and Gloria Sennett-

1135
01:20:19,500 --> 01:20:24,000
- and Gerald and Marjory Finn and
many relatives, friends and schoolmates.

1136
01:20:26,100 --> 01:20:29,000
The internment will follow
at Madison Memorial Park.

1137
01:20:29,800 --> 01:20:32,800
The family has asked me
to say a few words before we proceed.

1138
01:20:35,800 --> 01:20:38,800
No words I could say
would begin to express -

1139
01:20:39,400 --> 01:20:41,600
- the loss and grief.

1140
01:20:42,500 --> 01:20:45,500
One word that keeps
ringing in my ear -

1141
01:20:46,200 --> 01:20:47,500
- is "why?"

1142
01:20:47,800 --> 01:20:50,700
Why would God choose to take
this little boy from us?

1143
01:20:52,800 --> 01:20:55,400
Why? I cant give you an
answer to that question.

1144
01:20:55,400 --> 01:20:56,500
I can tell you -

1145
01:20:56,600 --> 01:20:59,600
God has chosen Thomas J.
for some very -

1146
01:20:59,800 --> 01:21:01,700
- special reason.

1147
01:21:02,500 --> 01:21:05,500
We must find solace in knowing
that Thomas J is in God's care.

1148
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:10,000
In that place, there is
no sorrow or suffering.

1149
01:21:12,100 --> 01:21:14,000
The lion lies with the lamb.

1150
01:21:14,300 --> 01:21:16,300
The day is not divided.

1151
01:21:16,800 --> 01:21:19,800
I'd like to read a passage
from the Bible.

1152
01:21:21,300 --> 01:21:24,000
This is Matthew 19.

1153
01:21:24,400 --> 01:21:26,600
"At one point, children were
brought to Him -

1154
01:21:26,600 --> 01:21:29,600
- that He might lay his
hands on them in prayer.

1155
01:21:30,300 --> 01:21:32,400
Disciples began to chastise Him.

1156
01:21:33,100 --> 01:21:36,100
But Jesus said,
"Let the children come to me.

1157
01:21:37,700 --> 01:21:39,300
Do not hinder them.

1158
01:21:39,300 --> 01:21:41,100
The kingdom of God -

1159
01:21:41,100 --> 01:21:42,600
- belongs to such as these."

1160
01:21:43,800 --> 01:21:45,700
He laid his hands on their heads -

1161
01:21:46,800 --> 01:21:49,000
- before he left that place."

1162
01:21:49,300 --> 01:21:52,200
Let us pray in silence.

1163
01:21:53,000 --> 01:21:55,900
Wanna go tree climbing, Thomas J?

1164
01:21:56,100 --> 01:21:57,400
His face hurts!

1165
01:21:57,800 --> 01:22:01,400
And where are his glasses?
He can't see without his glasses!

1166
01:22:02,200 --> 01:22:04,600
Put his glasses on!

1167
01:22:04,600 --> 01:22:05,900
Put on his glasses!

1168
01:22:07,800 --> 01:22:09,700
He was going to be an acrobat.

1169
01:22:09,700 --> 01:22:12,400
He's gone, sweetheart.

1170
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:18,200
Vada, wait!

1171
01:22:18,600 --> 01:22:20,100
Vada!

1172
01:22:34,200 --> 01:22:36,700
Vada, I was just on
my way to your house.

1173
01:22:36,700 --> 01:22:40,700
You all right?
I'm so sorry about Thomas J.

1174
01:22:41,800 --> 01:22:43,900
OK, we don't have to
talk about him!

1175
01:22:43,900 --> 01:22:46,900
It's okay.
We won't talk about him.

1176
01:22:47,300 --> 01:22:48,900
We won't talk about him.

1177
01:22:48,900 --> 01:22:51,900
Justin and Ronda say that I should
tell people what I feel.

1178
01:22:53,200 --> 01:22:55,600
Come here.
Sit down over here.

1179
01:22:57,700 --> 01:22:59,100
Mr. Bixler...

1180
01:23:00,800 --> 01:23:02,200
I love you.

1181
01:23:04,100 --> 01:23:06,800
I love you like my dad loves Shelly.

1182
01:23:07,200 --> 01:23:09,100
And I wanna live here.

1183
01:23:12,500 --> 01:23:14,300
I think your dad would miss you.

1184
01:23:14,500 --> 01:23:17,400
No, he wouldn't.
I can't go home.

1185
01:23:17,400 --> 01:23:19,300
Hank, I'll be ready in a second.

1186
01:23:19,400 --> 01:23:21,400
I can't find my other earring.

1187
01:23:22,200 --> 01:23:23,700
Suzanne, this is Vada.

1188
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:26,500
Vada, hi!

1189
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:28,100
I'm really sorry!

1190
01:23:28,200 --> 01:23:30,700
Could you give us a minute?

1191
01:23:34,200 --> 01:23:35,400
Who's that?

1192
01:23:36,600 --> 01:23:38,000
That's Suzanne.

1193
01:23:43,700 --> 01:23:46,100
She and I are gonna be
married this fall.

1194
01:23:47,100 --> 01:23:49,400
I was gonna bring her to class
next week.

1195
01:23:49,900 --> 01:23:51,700
I want her to hear your poem.

1196
01:23:54,100 --> 01:23:56,300
Please, honey.
I cared for him too.

1197
01:23:56,400 --> 01:23:58,400
Get away from me!

1198
01:23:58,400 --> 01:23:59,500
Vada!

1199
01:24:01,400 --> 01:24:03,600
Vada, sweetheart, don't...

1200
01:24:34,200 --> 01:24:36,500
<i>Why do you think people
want to get married?</i>

1201
01:24:37,400 --> 01:24:39,500
<i>When you get old,
you just have to.</i>

1202
01:24:44,600 --> 01:24:46,200
<i>Who's that with your dad?</i>

1203
01:24:47,200 --> 01:24:48,900
<i>That's my mother.</i>

1204
01:24:51,000 --> 01:24:53,500
<i>I'm gonna be an acrobat
when I grow up.</i>

1205
01:24:54,300 --> 01:24:55,300
<i>Vada?</i>

1206
01:24:56,400 --> 01:24:58,300
<i>Would you think of me?</i>

1207
01:24:58,800 --> 01:25:01,200
<i>If you don't get to marry
Mr. Bixler.</i>

1208
01:25:05,900 --> 01:25:08,100
<i>Now we're blood
brothers for life.</i>

1209
01:25:26,000 --> 01:25:27,900
Shelly, I'm sorry but we
haven't found her yet.

1210
01:25:27,900 --> 01:25:30,400
She can't be alone in the dark!

1211
01:25:31,900 --> 01:25:33,600
- We'll keep looking.
- We've been looking since this morning.

1212
01:25:33,600 --> 01:25:35,400
- Her teacher called...
- I know. You told us.

1213
01:25:36,200 --> 01:25:37,200
Vada?

1214
01:25:41,300 --> 01:25:42,800
Are you OK?

1215
01:25:43,400 --> 01:25:44,600
Oh, God!.

1216
01:25:46,400 --> 01:25:49,400
I should have told Thomas J.
he was my best friend.

1217
01:25:51,200 --> 01:25:53,000
I'm sure he knew.

1218
01:26:04,200 --> 01:26:08,200
Shelly, I stole some money
from your cookie jar -

1219
01:26:12,600 --> 01:26:13,900
- to pay for the writing class.
- It's okay.

1220
01:26:14,000 --> 01:26:19,000
I'll pay you back. Besides, I don't
think I'll ever go to class again.

1221
01:26:21,000 --> 01:26:24,000
Tell you what. You dedicate
your first book to me, -

1222
01:26:25,000 --> 01:26:27,200
- I'll forget the whole thing.

1223
01:26:27,200 --> 01:26:28,400
I will. I promise.

1224
01:26:28,500 --> 01:26:30,300
OK, get into bed.

1225
01:26:51,300 --> 01:26:53,700
- Good night.
- Good night.

1226
01:27:11,200 --> 01:27:12,500
She's here.

1227
01:27:30,000 --> 01:27:31,900
Did I kill my mother?

1228
01:27:32,100 --> 01:27:33,200
What?

1229
01:27:36,400 --> 01:27:39,400
The bees killed Thomas J.,
and I killed my mother.

1230
01:27:49,500 --> 01:27:51,600
Sweety, that wasn't your fault.

1231
01:27:53,200 --> 01:27:55,700
Things like that aren't
anybody's fault.

1232
01:27:56,100 --> 01:27:57,900
It just happened.

1233
01:28:02,500 --> 01:28:04,000
I found this.

1234
01:28:09,500 --> 01:28:12,500
I forgot about that picture.
Where'd you find it?

1235
01:28:13,000 --> 01:28:14,500
In the garage.

1236
01:28:15,900 --> 01:28:18,800
That little Chevy was your
mother's favorite car.

1237
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:21,500
What was my mama like?

1238
01:28:23,400 --> 01:28:26,400
She was pretty and kind.

1239
01:28:27,400 --> 01:28:29,500
She had your eyes.

1240
01:28:31,800 --> 01:28:34,000
Boy, did she love to laugh!

1241
01:28:36,400 --> 01:28:39,100
Sometimes when you laugh,
you sound just like her.

1242
01:28:39,300 --> 01:28:40,400
Really?

1243
01:28:42,400 --> 01:28:45,400
Know what she did when she found
out she was going to have you?

1244
01:28:47,200 --> 01:28:50,200
She came home and painted
this whole room pink.

1245
01:28:51,500 --> 01:28:53,700
She was so sure she was
going to have a little girl.

1246
01:28:54,100 --> 01:28:55,800
Do you miss her?

1247
01:28:57,900 --> 01:28:59,800
Yes, I did.

1248
01:28:59,800 --> 01:29:02,100
Very much, for a long time.

1249
01:29:04,000 --> 01:29:08,200
Even now, I get a little sad
when I think about a pretty flower -

1250
01:29:08,200 --> 01:29:11,200
- or a beautiful sunset
she would have liked.

1251
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:15,900
I think every time I see a climbing
tree, I'll think of Thomas J.

1252
01:29:17,400 --> 01:29:18,700
That's good.

1253
01:29:19,600 --> 01:29:21,300
Memories are good, sweetheart.

1254
01:29:23,200 --> 01:29:25,500
Vada, I'm sorry.

1255
01:29:27,000 --> 01:29:30,000
I was trying to keep it from you.

1256
01:29:32,900 --> 01:29:34,700
I just couldn't.

1257
01:29:38,200 --> 01:29:39,300
You're a good girl.

1258
01:29:39,600 --> 01:29:41,600
I want you to be happy.

1259
01:29:42,300 --> 01:29:44,600
Don't be an old grump like me.

1260
01:29:51,800 --> 01:29:53,800
See you in the morning.

1261
01:29:56,800 --> 01:29:58,000
Daddy?

1262
01:29:59,900 --> 01:30:02,300
It's not so bad to be like you.

1263
01:30:27,300 --> 01:30:29,700
Mrs. Sennett, how are you doing?

1264
01:30:31,700 --> 01:30:34,100
Some days I think I'll be okay -

1265
01:30:34,200 --> 01:30:37,900
- others I have to force myself -

1266
01:30:38,100 --> 01:30:39,800
- even to get out of bed.

1267
01:30:40,200 --> 01:30:44,500
I know it's crazy, but sometimes
I think he's just away at summer camp.

1268
01:30:45,500 --> 01:30:47,000
How's Veda?

1269
01:30:47,200 --> 01:30:50,200
She's doing much better.
She's just inside.

1270
01:30:51,100 --> 01:30:52,100
Vada?

1271
01:30:56,000 --> 01:30:57,500
Mrs. Sennett.

1272
01:30:57,900 --> 01:30:59,100
Vada!

1273
01:31:02,500 --> 01:31:05,000
I've been wanting to
come over to you.

1274
01:31:08,200 --> 01:31:10,600
Thomas J. had this on him.

1275
01:31:11,700 --> 01:31:14,100
I thought you might
like to have it.

1276
01:31:24,800 --> 01:31:26,800
You were such a good friend to him.

1277
01:31:28,000 --> 01:31:30,200
I hope you'll still come by
and visit me.

1278
01:31:30,600 --> 01:31:32,800
I will.
I promise.

1279
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:41,200
Mrs. Sennett?

1280
01:31:43,200 --> 01:31:47,500
Thomas J. will be all right.
My mother will take care of him.

1281
01:31:50,900 --> 01:31:52,600
Thank you, Vada.

1282
01:32:01,300 --> 01:32:03,400
"Encased in talent,
like a uniform -

1283
01:32:04,600 --> 01:32:07,000
- the rank of every poet
is well known.

1284
01:32:08,700 --> 01:32:11,200
They can amaze us
like a thunderstorm -

1285
01:32:12,800 --> 01:32:17,800
- or die so young
or live for years alone."

1286
01:32:21,400 --> 01:32:24,400
My advice to you
on our last class:

1287
01:32:26,200 --> 01:32:28,100
Be a thunderstorm!

1288
01:32:29,300 --> 01:32:31,500
What exactly do you mean by that?

1289
01:32:33,900 --> 01:32:35,200
I mean -

1290
01:32:36,000 --> 01:32:37,500
- be dangerous -

1291
01:32:39,200 --> 01:32:40,800
- and unpredictable.

1292
01:32:42,300 --> 01:32:44,300
And make a lot of noise.

1293
01:32:48,300 --> 01:32:49,300
Vada?

1294
01:32:53,500 --> 01:32:56,500
We missed you, man!
Give me a hug.

1295
01:33:01,000 --> 01:33:03,200
I was hoping you'd
stop by today.

1296
01:33:07,600 --> 01:33:09,200
Can't stay.

1297
01:33:09,700 --> 01:33:11,600
I just came to read my poem.

1298
01:33:11,700 --> 01:33:13,900
We'd love to hear it.

1299
01:33:19,900 --> 01:33:22,300
"Weeping willow with your tears
running down -

1300
01:33:22,900 --> 01:33:25,300
why do you always weep and frown?

1301
01:33:25,800 --> 01:33:28,600
Is it because he left you one day?

1302
01:33:28,700 --> 01:33:31,000
Is it because he could not stay?

1303
01:33:32,200 --> 01:33:34,700
On your branches he would swing.

1304
01:33:34,800 --> 01:33:37,800
Do you long for the happiness
that day would bring?

1305
01:33:38,300 --> 01:33:40,900
He found shelter in your shade.

1306
01:33:41,400 --> 01:33:44,400
You thought his laughter
would never fade.

1307
01:33:45,200 --> 01:33:47,900
Weeping willow, stop your tears.

1308
01:33:48,500 --> 01:33:51,100
There is something
to calm your fears.

1309
01:33:51,900 --> 01:33:54,900
You think death has ripped you
forever apart.

1310
01:33:55,700 --> 01:33:58,400
But I know he'll always
be in your heart."

1311
01:34:08,300 --> 01:34:10,600
- Hi, Judy.
- Vada.

1312
01:34:10,600 --> 01:34:12,700
<i>Things are a little better these days.</i>

1313
01:34:12,800 --> 01:34:14,700
<i>I finally swallowed that chicken bone.</i>

1314
01:34:14,800 --> 01:34:17,300
<i>Judy and I are going to be
in the same homeroom.</i>

1315
01:34:17,600 --> 01:34:20,600
<i>And the Republican Party
just renominated Mr. Nixon.</i>

1316
01:34:22,000 --> 01:34:32,000
The Temptations: My Girl
